Explanation

The data that was used in this report was the latitude and longitude of many points across the Earths surface. Each point had correlated with it a time (for example, 1960-01-01), precipitation, and temperature. In this report, I narrowed the observations down to only those observations in April of 1960, 1986, and 2014. Furthermore, I focused only on temperature and not precipitation. Temperature is represented by the monthly mean in Celsius.

It may be hard to detect differences in the graphs, but I draw your attention to several places.

Differences from 1960-1986

Each of the three sections that I circle here have odd changes in temperature. Youll notice one of the places has large red dots despite being up in Canada strange, no?

Differences from 1960-2014

In section 1, we see that Canada and Alaska now have much more smooth temperature gradients and are trending toward being warmer. Spots and pockets of cold that were there in 1960 are now gone. In section 2, we see that things have heated up considerably; it used to be much more blue.

To draw your attention to these areas with more force, I present to you the difference in April 2014s temperatures and April 1960s temperatures:

Temperature differences

Many spots are either purple (small gain in temperature) or red (large gain in temperature). There are some areas where the temperature did drop a little, but notice how many parts of North America have warmed significantly? Theres a huge difference between April 2014 and April 1960! So even if the global yearly average temperature only rises by one or two degrees, it can still result in massive temperature spikes like this.

While proper conclusions cannot be garnered from just these three points of data, it definitely fits in with the theory of global climate change. It was exactly what Id expected to see, though the temperature increase in just fifty years is astonishing.
